Integration tests for orphan-artifact reconciliation: verifies `find_orphan_artifacts` and the `check`/`prune`/`update` runner paths correctly identify and remove `.context/` sidecars whose source files were deleted, moved, or scoped out of the walker's target list.

Uses two harnesses: an in-memory `FakeFs` (implementing `ctx_summarize::fs::Fs`) for hermetic orphan-detection logic, and real tmpdir fixtures (via `seeded_fixture`) for exercising `check_run`/`prune_run`/`update_run` against actual filesystem state. `StubAgent` counts `complete` calls so tests can assert pruning never bills the model.

Key invariants asserted here (not just documented): orphan detection reduces both "source deleted" and "source scoped out" to the same "not in targets" check — the walker's target list is the sole scope authority. A deleted *file* leaf is caught via hash-diff and deduplicated out of `orphan_artifacts` (appears only in `orphan_leaves`); a deleted *directory* subtree is invisible to the hash diff (sidecar never loaded) and is caught only by `find_orphan_artifacts`/reconciliation — these are different mechanisms covering different cases. `.context/intent.md`, `.context/README.md`, and the runtime dirs `.cache`/`.reports` are always spared by pruning, at any nesting depth. `check_run` is strictly read-only. `prune_run` sweeps emptied directories. `update_run` prunes orphans without any agent call when the rest of the tree is hash-fresh — pruning is a no-model operation.

`prompts_path()` resolves prompt files relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`, independent of test cwd; `test_dir(label)` gives per-test tmpdir isolation under the system temp dir, manually cleaned up at the end of each real-fs test.